The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing – a virtual operator that requires traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive operators in Europe has already written many times on Mobil.cz.
After all, it has also confirmed ČTÚ, which has noted that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission on the regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and cover highly over 100 %.
Instead mobile telephony operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ) is also often emphasized by Pavel Dvořák, who in the past expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network may no longer have many possibilities. (Moreover, it may be difficult to find other frequencies.)
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant price fall, to which traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices were resounding in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we must not go too far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In only half a year this operator managed to conquer more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs among the other U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more concrete group-trap.
In order to actually function, it is sufficient for many less customers than for a traditional operator.
They do not carry behind, i.e., relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low price, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
For example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that costs at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-strike not recently.
This operator aims to say so specifically about men.
"The real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and you can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
The press spokesperson for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there will never be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will happen rather in the other countries in our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are not definitely very much in favour of this thought.
Rather, they try to do everything because no potential competitor is created.
For a while it has not hidden its interest in the start of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefonika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And first, it's better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all the Czech operators of the mobile network.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," says the spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl group.
So maybe there'll be better times.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will have to have it by the end of the year.
But for now around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a virtual operator in full capacity.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press section of Telefónnika O2.
The specificity of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
The press spokesman for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the declaration O2: "For now we have not noticed any vital and advantageous commercial projects for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we should have already had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered at the horizon."
Vodafone concentrates its attention rather than reaching its 3G licence requests.
Adds Miroslav Čepický: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the context of spending and infrastructure sharing.
Let us consider this, from a customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities - with complicating operators
The attitude of mobile operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thereby to lower profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
Disturbing around the creation U:fon testify that when operators hold to something they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing towards ČTÚ during the period of creation of U:fon to the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from ČTÚ's web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which you do not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has been largely strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that another competitor’s entry would place on him and above all on his high demand services.”
The attitude of mobile telephony operators is, however, quite surprising to the complete disinterest by Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of ČTÚ that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere with economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, concerns the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract of rental of the necessary infrastructure between mobile operator and virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, from the section for external relations ÚOHS, in the answer to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators might not be surprising.
Instead of the office which must defend the interests of consumers and, above all, take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of his position on the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their market entry has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
But of course the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of UOHS.
It is really shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question as to whether it is really just a coincidence, is put on its own.
Similarly, the same price of petrol for all gasolines is clearly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so he does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for his behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator it is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has - at the end of the accounts logically - the monopoly of his network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum alert that three mobile operators proceed so strangely similar.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS is kept out of the whole matter.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected to improve the situation.
This is what the representatives of UOHS need to know better than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it, when no one looks
While these pseudo-virtual operators remain unaccompanied, some of them even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multi-level marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the pre-determined persons.
The magic lies in the fact that the company against the operator appears as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a sale.
"If the cases were to be presented, of which we will be interested, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions, and it could result in the conclusion of cooperation with that company," responded to the question Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile telephone operators.
Especially in the cases of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
The activity of these companies derives a non-differentiating profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
These must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile operators "
But this ought to be a little weird about ČTÚ.
In addition, there is another issue for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UUOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant decrease in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators were trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small market, at the too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases, the regulators have intervened in defence not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and to him other ones have been approached.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators start from one another all the time as a boiling potato.
For our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes them more than comfortable.
But we don't throw the sponge.
If the backstage information is right and the virtual operator will appear really soon from us, the Czech mobile phone market will get back on track.
If one of the operators consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only difficultly ÚOHS could remain unable to reject (discrimination) other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek, on the occasion of the Czech State's Day of Recognition, presented in a solemn way the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov m alkj".
The new recording of the hymn was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, chorus step and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem revisions are Otakar Jerériaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz site you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Earlier he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the variants alone, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and also the choir, have the clear statement, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year the 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde domov męj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by music by František Škroupa.
He bought popularity and people spontaneously made it his own.
The first stanza of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
