Talking in the Sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who speak while sleeping.
The first time it happens, at most it takes a scare, but it doesn't really matter very much.
This is a benign alteration of the sleep defined dreamword.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely most of you told me that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with more regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (doing pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it may be associated with very high fever stages, stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
Even the intensity with which it appears to be extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite occurs (screams, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there are any issues that are generating anomalous state of anxiety as a result of the situation.
We said that this is a benign alteration, therefore, there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, on the other hand, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to bed.
Propose quiet games and avoid television programs or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleepy words appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day will not remember anything that happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's happening, and you'll interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you appear very anxious and episodes have a certain frequency it is best to consult a doctor or check where there is such anxiety in your child.
