The meeting - The blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDecary, had every reason to rejoice, for Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shocked by the scandal of infected blood in the years 1980-1990.
As we know, national reserves of blood managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to clarify the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying to draw up a report, some provinces have set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, only 38% of the people stated that they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to the continued efforts to improve the safety of blood withdrawals and field research over the following years, we have regained the confidence of the public," he said before he was proud that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells of those who have been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we did not know at all whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
We have therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau relations, according to which when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, take exclusion measures.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than one month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted by infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it has made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the identification of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow donors to directly recognize the presence of the virus and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TAN have allowed to reduce the window period, since the person has contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be identified in the blood through our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus significantly diminished.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion occurs.
I believe that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of the Hema-Québec leadership.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, Chikungunya virus appeared on the Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in blood by an insect.
We need to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before we stress that, in addition to having safe resources, the Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Necessity increases as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average constitute only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 years and who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
The cases of poverty are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and cannot make donations anymore.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today life is so frantic that it is difficult to find one hour to donate blood," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Hema-Québec that manages the only public bank of the blood of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, there is plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can help cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth sample of cordon blood and we plan to take more than a thousand of them every year.
You should start to propose them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of taking cordon blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't access you," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
