Mp3 readers under charge, put the hearing at risk
Listening to high volume music for a prolonged period of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a statement published in Brussels cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging Health Risks recently identified (Csseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion - we read in the note - it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day keeping the high volume apparatus risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From scientific findings - the EU responsible continues - there is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is that we need to raise consumers' awareness and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the widespread use of portable musical equipment and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - concludes the EU Executive - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical equipment and related equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns about hearing damage can arise from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment when listening to high volume (more than 89 decibel) music for only 5 hours per week exceed the current limits on maximum permitted noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would cover 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
