The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the 700 billion-dollar rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
It confirms the New York Times of yesterday by informing us that the ongoing crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast, moderate, favourable to federal institutions and business community, and its new, conservative, hostile to "the Washington ones" and the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and South states.
The soul, by the way, that became prepotently alive by the vote I said at the beginning.
This is, however, only one example of the changes, the major changes, which the current economic earthquake may pre-announce or already let us see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not here only.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of incubation phenomena for a long time and in the new climate they solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-upgradation, the extraordinary re-launching, of the dual category State-sovereignity in relation to a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions, which have, yes, close links with the outside world, but first of all they see very much involved in the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
Which immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems largely out of play or has little to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union that divides as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies cannot decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each State that all are expected to intervene, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you arrive at close are only the States that possess economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in sixth place.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which no market or international organisation can possibly have the same extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis puts on the constitutional-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor that is very closely related to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we were now in the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized that our future will have to deal increasingly with those very little material things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are nevertheless bound in absolute terms to a confined space, to a territory.
So that whoever is sovereign, certainly owns several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
However, I come to the second novelty that predisposes a fracture.
Those who say Territory, State, Government, inevitably say Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who can take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discretion for existing leadership, economic species, turned out to be so inadequate and filled with shadow zones.
And together something even deeper and in a certain disturbing sense: a discreet, an insufficient, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
That is to say, it seems that in many sectors of the population, the belief that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far at large, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall acceptance of the term, having made their own time and being increasingly alien to the views of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branch but powerful movement of dellegitimacy of the ruling classes and traditional political arrangements, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolts" elections or in the sudden developments of the collective moods of these last last few times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Baviera to the collapse of workers' consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy has something to do).
